                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18311201-247-off1316 t18311201-247-crimeloc1319"></join> for about ten minutes - when I returned, I missed three loaves; I saw the bread and the prisoner in custody - these are the loaves.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18311201-247-person1885">
                  HENRY 
                  GARNET
               <interp inst="t18311201-247-person1885" type="surname" value="GARNET"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18311201-247-person1885" type="given" value="HENRY"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18311201-247-person1885" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a Policeman. On the 25th of<xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="183112010109"></xptr>November, I saw the prisoner on the square side, with these loaves under his arm; when he saw me he ran fast -I went and took him, and asked where he got the bread; he said, "Where did I get it?" as I was taking him along, he threw the loaves into a basket at the corner of Orchard-street, and said, "What is a fellow to do?" he said he had had nothing to eat for two days - he had not a farthing on him, and was nearly naked.</p>
               <p>Prisoner's Defence. I was in the greatest distress, and seeing the basket, I took them; I should not have taken three, but they were stuck together.</p>
               <p>
